1
00:02:05,358 --> 00:02:06,818
What am I working on?

2
00:02:07,435 --> 00:02:10,025
Something that will
change the world...

3
00:02:10,231 --> 00:02:11,981
...and human life as we know it.

4
00:02:12,348 --> 00:02:15,898
Change it a lot or just a bit?
Be more specific.

5
00:02:16,472 --> 00:02:19,062
You want me to be more
specific here with...

6
00:02:19,268 --> 00:02:22,688
...half the scientific
community eavesdropping?

7
00:02:23,343 --> 00:02:24,433
Where else?

8
00:02:26,219 --> 00:02:29,099
You could come back to my lab.

9
00:02:30,053 --> 00:02:31,633
I'll make cappuccino.

10
00:02:31,841 --> 00:02:33,971
I have a Faema of my own.

11
00:02:34,177 --> 00:02:36,927
It's not the dilettante's
plastic model.

12
00:02:37,213 --> 00:02:41,473
It's a restaurant espresso machine
with an eagle on top.

13
00:02:42,466 --> 00:02:45,046
Somehow I get the feeling
you don't get out much.

14
00:02:45,382 --> 00:02:48,592
-You can tell that?
-Yes.

15
00:02:58,584 --> 00:03:01,794
You're making a mistake.
I think you really want to talk to me.

16
00:03:02,079 --> 00:03:04,999
Sorry. I have three other interviews
before this party is over.

17
00:03:05,244 --> 00:03:07,874
But they don't have something
that will change the world.

18
00:03:08,330 --> 00:03:09,450
They say they do.

19
00:03:10,827 --> 00:03:12,417
Yeah but they're lying.

20
00:03:12,914 --> 00:03:14,034
I'm not.

21
00:03:20,244 --> 00:03:21,454
Are you sick?

22
00:03:22,111 --> 00:03:24,831
No-- Sure.

23
00:03:25,366 --> 00:03:27,616
You're not a very good drunk.

24
00:03:28,692 --> 00:03:30,952
No, I'm always like this.
It's the...

25
00:03:31,698 --> 00:03:36,618
...motion sickness. When I was a kid,
I puked on my tricycle.

26
00:03:38,149 --> 00:03:39,779
I hate vehicles.

27
00:03:39,986 --> 00:03:41,566
Should I drive slowly?

28
00:03:41,814 --> 00:03:44,364
No. Turn left.
We're almost there.

29
00:04:01,936 --> 00:04:02,976
This is it?

30
00:04:03,304 --> 00:04:06,774
It's cleaner on the inside.

31
00:04:16,426 --> 00:04:17,716
Please.

32
00:04:48,331 --> 00:04:51,291
Listen.
Maybe this is a bad idea.

33
00:04:52,495 --> 00:04:54,125
Too late.

34
00:04:54,702 --> 00:04:58,332
You've already seen them.
You can't leave here alive.

35
00:05:01,373 --> 00:05:02,623
I haven't seen anything.

36
00:05:04,159 --> 00:05:05,369
Those.

37
00:05:11,160 --> 00:05:13,370
Designer phone booths.

38
00:05:13,576 --> 00:05:15,576
Very cute.

39
00:05:16,612 --> 00:05:19,822
I bet you have a really neat
jukebox in here too.

40
00:05:20,107 --> 00:05:21,407
Over there?

41
00:05:22,154 --> 00:05:23,364
No.

42
00:05:25,689 --> 00:05:27,949
No.
This is the...

43
00:05:28,895 --> 00:05:33,025
...prototype of those.
The first one I had made.

44
00:05:33,648 --> 00:05:37,648
It works, but it's clunky.

45
00:05:50,185 --> 00:05:51,975
I call them telepods.

46
00:05:53,011 --> 00:05:54,721
They're controlled by this.

47
00:05:55,388 --> 00:05:57,348
Thank God for that.

48
00:05:58,843 --> 00:06:01,933
What do these
phones booths do?

49
00:06:02,139 --> 00:06:03,179
Telepods.

50
00:06:07,841 --> 00:06:11,181
Okay, I need an object.

51
00:06:13,463 --> 00:06:15,923
Do you have something that is...

52
00:06:16,589 --> 00:06:19,719
...personal I can use?
Something uniquely you?

53
00:06:20,463 --> 00:06:22,093
An item of clothing or jewelry?

54
00:06:23,090 --> 00:06:24,250
You kidding?

55
00:06:24,548 --> 00:06:25,878
No, I'm serious.

56
00:06:29,541 --> 00:06:32,291
Okay. Here it goes.

57
00:06:51,241 --> 00:06:53,081
I don't wear jewelry.

58
00:07:00,278 --> 00:07:02,028
It's nice.

59
00:07:15,237 --> 00:07:17,487
Brundle, Seth.

60
00:07:36,847 --> 00:07:38,267
Watch the stocking.

61
00:08:07,964 --> 00:08:08,964
Well?

62
00:08:10,341 --> 00:08:11,591
Great.

63
00:08:12,088 --> 00:08:16,048
A giant microwave oven. I'm glad
I didn't give you my Rolex.

64
00:08:16,253 --> 00:08:17,503
If I had a Rolex.

65
00:08:17,711 --> 00:08:19,881
You're missing the point.
Look.

66
00:08:27,827 --> 00:08:29,247
Teleportation?

67
00:08:31,082 --> 00:08:32,582
Please.

68
00:08:48,408 --> 00:08:50,028
Wait a minute.

69
00:08:51,574 --> 00:08:52,864
Is that a hologram?

70
00:08:53,401 --> 00:08:56,741
-Where's my stocking?
-That's it.

71
00:08:57,945 --> 00:08:58,905
Pick it up.

72
00:09:11,776 --> 00:09:13,776
I don't get it.

73
00:09:14,642 --> 00:09:15,772
What happened?

74
00:09:15,980 --> 00:09:18,520
You get it but you can't handle it.

75
00:09:19,894 --> 00:09:23,684
Your stocking has just
been teleported...

76
00:09:24,058 --> 00:09:27,398
...from one pod to another.

77
00:09:27,604 --> 00:09:30,474
Disintegrated there
and reintegrated there.

78
00:09:31,219 --> 00:09:32,309
Sort of.

79
00:09:33,475 --> 00:09:36,055
It will change the world
as we know it, right?

80
00:09:45,379 --> 00:09:46,929
This is incredible.

81
00:09:47,136 --> 00:09:48,926
It's not possible, is it?

82
00:09:49,383 --> 00:09:51,173
How have you kept this quiet?

83
00:09:52,050 --> 00:09:53,380
Please sit down.

84
00:09:53,797 --> 00:09:55,887
How could you do this alone?

85
00:09:56,543 --> 00:09:58,293
I don't work alone.

86
00:09:58,501 --> 00:10:01,011
There's stuff in there I don't
understand. I'm really a...

87
00:10:01,207 --> 00:10:02,917
...systems manager.
I farm out...

88
00:10:03,124 --> 00:10:06,254
...pieces to men more
brilliant than I. I say:

89
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:11,340
"Design me a molecular analyzer, "
and they do. I just assemble it.

90
00:10:11,582 --> 00:10:14,292
None of them knows
what the project really is.

91
00:10:17,744 --> 00:10:21,254
And the money? Bartok
Science Industries financed this?

92
00:10:21,868 --> 00:10:24,748
But they leave me alone
because I'm not expensive.

93
00:10:25,164 --> 00:10:28,084
They know they'll own
whatever it is.

94
00:10:28,279 --> 00:10:29,829
You haven't told them?

95
00:10:30,197 --> 00:10:31,117
When I'm ready.

96
00:10:32,653 --> 00:10:34,163
Wait a second.

97
00:10:36,278 --> 00:10:37,238
What's that?

98
00:10:38,575 --> 00:10:40,035
To get the quotes right.

99
00:10:40,402 --> 00:10:42,742
Quotes? No.

100
00:10:42,949 --> 00:10:45,199
This was personal.
Don't write about it.

101
00:10:46,524 --> 00:10:48,984
What do you mean?
I'm a journalist.

102
00:10:49,230 --> 00:10:52,070
-Oh, no.
-You knew that.

103
00:10:53,195 --> 00:10:57,275
I made a mistake. I shouldn't
have shown you this. I'm very sorry.

104
00:10:57,479 --> 00:11:02,359
Particle Magazine sent me
to get a story.

105
00:11:02,562 --> 00:11:04,942
This is the most
exciting story ever.

106
00:11:05,148 --> 00:11:07,688
No. Absolutely not.
I must have that tape.

107
00:11:07,894 --> 00:11:09,394
-Please.
-You can't do that.

108
00:11:09,642 --> 00:11:10,932
Don't write a story.

109
00:11:11,140 --> 00:11:13,060
I'd never have told
this stuff to a journalist.

110
00:11:13,267 --> 00:11:16,857
-But you told it to me.
-I suppose I did but--

111
00:11:17,261 --> 00:11:18,971
-Sure did.
-Now wait a minute.

112
00:11:20,057 --> 00:11:22,347
Come here.
What about your stocking?

113
00:11:22,764 --> 00:11:24,724
Keep it for good luck.

114
00:11:35,756 --> 00:11:39,346
I say: "Design me a
molecular analyzer, " and they do.

115
00:11:39,550 --> 00:11:40,630
I just assemble it.

116
00:11:41,008 --> 00:11:43,088
None of them knows
what the project really is.

117
00:11:46,171 --> 00:11:48,751
And the money? Bartok
Science Industries financed this?

118
00:11:49,007 --> 00:11:52,007
But they leave me alone
because I'm not expensive.

119
00:11:52,922 --> 00:11:55,422
They know they'll own
whatever it is.

120
00:11:56,786 --> 00:11:59,046
Well, that's it.

121
00:12:00,621 --> 00:12:01,711
What do you think?

122
00:12:02,459 --> 00:12:03,619
It's a joke.

123
00:12:03,827 --> 00:12:04,667
What?

124
00:12:04,875 --> 00:12:06,455
He's conning you.

125
00:12:06,703 --> 00:12:09,163
It's an old nightclub routine.
The two cabinets.

126
00:12:09,579 --> 00:12:12,669
-You fell for it.
-Wait a minute.

127
00:12:12,864 --> 00:12:14,704
-That was no--
-Are we having lunch?

128
00:12:15,201 --> 00:12:18,541
That was no nightclub routine.
I was there. I saw it.

129
00:12:24,528 --> 00:12:25,778
Sure.

130
00:12:26,365 --> 00:12:27,865
Send him in.

131
00:12:29,152 --> 00:12:31,492
You must have made an impression.

132
00:12:31,858 --> 00:12:32,908
What do you mean?

133
00:12:33,486 --> 00:12:36,116
Your magician followed you here.

134
00:12:38,938 --> 00:12:41,948
I'm Stathis Borans,
editor of Particle Magazine.

135
00:12:42,153 --> 00:12:45,193
-Seth Brundle.
-I know who you are.

136
00:12:46,517 --> 00:12:49,937
Why don't you two use my office?
I've gotta run.

137
00:12:50,352 --> 00:12:53,522
If you plan to make anything
disappear, let me know.

138
00:12:53,767 --> 00:12:57,277
I have an assistant editor
who's outlived his usefulness.

139
00:13:02,226 --> 00:13:03,516
You didn't waste time.

140
00:13:04,393 --> 00:13:06,433
I'm not getting any younger.

141
00:13:08,886 --> 00:13:11,136
He wasn't impressed by your tape?

142
00:13:12,761 --> 00:13:14,301
He thinks you're a con man.

143
00:13:17,514 --> 00:13:18,464
Excellent.

144
00:13:19,552 --> 00:13:21,722
Let's see what the people
at Omni think about it.

145
00:13:21,928 --> 00:13:24,218
No, no.
Listen, Veronica....

146
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:28,722
I've come here to say one magic word.

147
00:13:30,047 --> 00:13:30,927
Yeah?

148
00:13:31,834 --> 00:13:32,924
Cheeseburger.

149
00:13:38,375 --> 00:13:40,585
I've been working alone too long.

150
00:13:42,250 --> 00:13:45,630
I have a strong urge
to talk about what I'm doing.

151
00:13:46,624 --> 00:13:49,414
But if this gets out now...

152
00:13:49,620 --> 00:13:51,620
...Veronica, it'll kill me.

153
00:13:52,286 --> 00:13:54,996
The Bartok people
and my colleagues will kill me.

154
00:13:55,991 --> 00:13:57,291
It's not ready yet.

155
00:13:57,539 --> 00:13:58,959
It works okay.

156
00:13:59,286 --> 00:14:01,536
No, something important's missing.

157
00:14:01,953 --> 00:14:02,953
Yeah?

158
00:14:04,240 --> 00:14:05,330
Yeah.

159
00:14:07,365 --> 00:14:08,325
What?

160
00:14:10,820 --> 00:14:13,740
I can only teleport inanimate objects.

161
00:14:16,612 --> 00:14:18,862
What happens when you
teleport living things?

162
00:14:20,607 --> 00:14:21,697
Not while we're eating.

163
00:14:22,484 --> 00:14:24,524
Can't be worse than this.

164
00:14:27,987 --> 00:14:30,657
You're not doing
a good job of convincing me.

165
00:14:30,853 --> 00:14:34,523
I think I should tell
the world about this now.

166
00:14:35,147 --> 00:14:36,817
You should tell it...

167
00:14:38,851 --> 00:14:41,351
...but not yet.
What do you have so far?

168
00:14:42,187 --> 00:14:43,687
Enough to make you nervous.

169
00:14:43,894 --> 00:14:47,394
Why not get more? Make me
your major project, a book.

170
00:14:47,599 --> 00:14:49,559
Not a magazine article.

171
00:14:49,766 --> 00:14:53,056
Follow me and my work,
day by day in detail.

172
00:14:53,721 --> 00:14:57,771
I have no life, so there's nothing
for you to interfere with.

173
00:14:57,975 --> 00:15:01,685
Research the background.
Cover the process.

174
00:15:02,888 --> 00:15:06,178
"The complete record of the most
earth-shattering invention ever.

175
00:15:06,423 --> 00:15:09,883
The one that ended
all concepts of transport...

176
00:15:10,088 --> 00:15:13,048
...of borders and frontiers,
of time and space."

177
00:15:15,670 --> 00:15:18,420
The book will end with me...

178
00:15:18,626 --> 00:15:22,096
...transporting myself
from one telepod to another.

179
00:15:22,291 --> 00:15:23,591
That's what's missing.

180
00:15:26,795 --> 00:15:28,215
Wait for me that long?

181
00:16:15,857 --> 00:16:17,857
What are you doing here?

182
00:16:18,273 --> 00:16:21,153
I was in the neighborhood.
Felt a bit scummy.

183
00:16:23,227 --> 00:16:24,687
Rough day.

184
00:16:35,480 --> 00:16:36,890
How'd you get in?

185
00:16:38,386 --> 00:16:40,356
I have a key, remember?

186
00:16:40,762 --> 00:16:41,932
You gave it to me.

187
00:16:42,390 --> 00:16:43,930
I should've changed the lock.

188
00:16:45,346 --> 00:16:46,306
You didn't.

189
00:16:50,299 --> 00:16:53,929
That's because unconsciously...

190
00:16:55,672 --> 00:16:58,972
...you still want me to come back,
move in again.

191
00:16:59,257 --> 00:17:00,387
No.

192
00:17:01,094 --> 00:17:05,594
That's because, consciously,
I'm lazy and disorganized.

193
00:17:11,000 --> 00:17:12,750
Your new playmate's interesting.

194
00:17:12,958 --> 00:17:14,338
What playmate?

195
00:17:14,705 --> 00:17:16,415
The nightclub act.

196
00:17:18,290 --> 00:17:19,540
Brundle.

197
00:17:20,837 --> 00:17:22,997
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

198
00:17:24,661 --> 00:17:28,211
I was wrong.
He's really quite brilliant.

199
00:17:29,874 --> 00:17:33,624
He led the F32 team.
Remember that?

200
00:17:34,867 --> 00:17:37,957
An inch away from the
Nobel Prize for physics.

201
00:17:38,452 --> 00:17:40,742
He was only 20 at the time.

202
00:17:41,368 --> 00:17:45,288
I'm not going to do Brundle.
Maybe the Psychology Today gig.

203
00:17:45,902 --> 00:17:47,072
That's not like you.

204
00:17:48,868 --> 00:17:51,118
Are you getting out or am I?

205
00:17:52,822 --> 00:17:56,452
I'll go. Shall I return later
and tuck you in?

206
00:17:57,066 --> 00:17:58,986
No. Key.

207
00:18:01,021 --> 00:18:02,611
I'll keep it...

208
00:18:03,607 --> 00:18:04,987
...for old time's sake.

209
00:18:07,232 --> 00:18:09,442
You're a petty schmuck.

210
00:18:30,510 --> 00:18:32,930
Initiate in 5 seconds.

211
00:19:53,105 --> 00:19:55,445
I've got to do this, Seth.

212
00:19:55,692 --> 00:19:57,612
Talk to the tape.
Get in the habit.

213
00:19:57,938 --> 00:19:59,728
The world will want to know
what you're thinking.

214
00:19:59,936 --> 00:20:01,896
"Fuck" is what I'm thinking!

215
00:20:02,392 --> 00:20:03,602
Good.

216
00:20:03,810 --> 00:20:06,310
The world will want to know that.

217
00:20:07,765 --> 00:20:09,935
What else?
Why didn't it work?

218
00:20:10,681 --> 00:20:13,941
I think it turned the baboon
inside out.

219
00:20:17,222 --> 00:20:18,312
Why?

220
00:20:19,718 --> 00:20:23,978
It can't deal with the flesh,
only inanimate objects.

221
00:20:26,848 --> 00:20:28,428
It must be my fault.

222
00:20:29,345 --> 00:20:30,305
Why?

223
00:20:32,880 --> 00:20:35,760
Computers only know
what you tell them.

224
00:20:37,344 --> 00:20:40,844
I don't know enough about the flesh.
I have to learn.

225
00:20:45,463 --> 00:20:47,713
I don't want to talk now.

226
00:21:07,082 --> 00:21:09,162
Do you ever change your clothes?

227
00:21:10,578 --> 00:21:12,038
What?

228
00:21:12,825 --> 00:21:15,825
You're always wearing
the same clothes.

229
00:21:19,156 --> 00:21:23,536
No, these are clean.
I change my clothes every day.

230
00:21:32,817 --> 00:21:35,237
Five sets of exactly the same clothes?

231
00:21:35,863 --> 00:21:36,943
Learned it from Einstein.

232
00:21:38,359 --> 00:21:39,939
This way I don't have to...

233
00:21:40,147 --> 00:21:44,527
...expend any thought on what to wear.
I grab the next set on the rack.

234
00:21:51,181 --> 00:21:55,021
I bought some steaks.
Can I make you one?

235
00:21:56,104 --> 00:21:57,264
We could go out.

236
00:21:58,521 --> 00:21:59,681
Cheeseburger?

237
00:22:03,055 --> 00:22:06,435
No, we don't have to go there.

238
00:22:15,008 --> 00:22:18,178
You're very cute. You know that?

239
00:22:19,093 --> 00:22:20,173
Am I?

240
00:23:00,205 --> 00:23:01,865
-What happened?
-On my back.

241
00:23:04,030 --> 00:23:06,450
Something's stuck to your back.

242
00:23:06,657 --> 00:23:08,577
Pull it off.

243
00:23:16,822 --> 00:23:18,322
Sorry.

244
00:23:20,108 --> 00:23:22,108
I wondered where this was.

245
00:23:22,315 --> 00:23:25,985
-Do you have any disinfectant?
-No, that's okay.

246
00:23:26,189 --> 00:23:27,899
I'll kiss it for you.

247
00:23:36,645 --> 00:23:40,395
Sorry.
I just want to eat you up.

248
00:23:42,017 --> 00:23:45,317
That's why old ladies
pinch babies' cheeks.

249
00:23:45,513 --> 00:23:49,023
It's the flesh. It makes you crazy.

250
00:23:50,935 --> 00:23:52,305
Ronnie. Ronnie.

251
00:23:57,426 --> 00:23:59,686
You want to try an experiment?

252
00:24:00,971 --> 00:24:01,971
Sure.

253
00:24:53,658 --> 00:24:56,868
Eat this.
I need an objective opinion.

254
00:25:05,981 --> 00:25:10,281
It could use some finesse,
but it tastes like a steak.

255
00:25:16,147 --> 00:25:19,107
Now try this teleported half.

256
00:25:19,352 --> 00:25:23,732
-A monkey just came apart in there.
-Baboon. Eat.

257
00:25:28,689 --> 00:25:29,979
It tastes funny.

258
00:25:30,307 --> 00:25:32,897
-Funny how?
-It tastes...

259
00:25:34,062 --> 00:25:35,022
...synthetic.

260
00:25:39,135 --> 00:25:40,515
What have we proved?

261
00:25:41,302 --> 00:25:46,432
The computer is giving us
its interpretation...

262
00:25:46,924 --> 00:25:50,764
...of a steak. It's translating it,
rethinking it...

